<H3> <TI>   Cambodia's Sirivut Condemns Thai Refugee Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cambodia's Sirivut Condemns Thai Refugee Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0304113094 Bangkok KRUNGTHEP THURAKIT in Thai 3 Apr 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> BK0304113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok KRUNGTHEP THURAKIT </F>
<F P=105>  Thai </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cambodian Foreign Minister Prince Norodom Sirivut 
issued a statement on 2 April in which he expressed opposition 
to the Thai Government's immediate repatriation of some 30,000 
Cambodian refugees to areas under Khmer Rouge control. He said 
he strongly protested the incorrect move taken by the Thai 
Government. He said it constituted a real violation of human 
rights. The statement was addressed to Sadako Ogata, the United 
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees. 
  Ogata, the Washington government, and humanitarian 
organizations formally protested the repatriation to the Thai 
Government but Thai leaders denied the allegation. 
  Cambodian refugees, mostly women and children, fled the 
fighting in Pailin after government forces took over the Khmer 
Rouge stronghold in the province on 19 March. The Thai 
military, however, insisted that the Cambodian refugees wanted 
to return to their respective areas under Khmer Rouge control. 
Nobody has been allowed into the area for observation. 
  The Cambodian foreign minister said that he profoundly 
regrets the Thai Government's inhuman act, which contradicts 
efforts by human rights organizations to achieve equality and to 
find a solution to human rights abuse. During his visit to 
Thailand last week for talks with the Thai Government on the 
problem of Cambodian refugees, the Cambodian foreign minister 
adopted an entirely different attitude regarding his reproach of 
the Thai Government. 

</TEXT>

