<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliamentary Union Condemns U.S. War Moves </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliamentary Union Condemns U.S. War Moves </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0204102794 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1013 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0204102794 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 2 (KCNA) -- Yi Mong-ho, head of the 
DPRK Parliamentary Union delegation, speaking at the 91st 
conference of the Inter-Parliamentary Union (IPU) on March 25, 
warned that the United States should be held entirely 
responsible for the catastrophic consequences to be entailed by 
its war moves. 
  Recalling that although four steps of simultaneous action 
were agreed upon at the DPRK-USA contact in New York in 
February, the U.S. side has fulfilled none of its obligations, 
leaving its promise an empty word, he said: 
  "The United States frustrated the third round of DPRK-USA 
talks with the far-fetched argument that the inspection of the 
DPRK by the International Atomic Energy Agency was not 
satisfactory, and decided to deploy Patriot missiles in South 
Korea, threatening the resumption of 'Team Spirit' joint 
military exercises. 
  "We will not regard it as our duty any longer to guarantee 
the continuity of safeguards since the United States and the 
IAEA intentionally distorted the results of inspection for the 
continuity of safeguards and are abusing them as an excuse for 
increasing pressure on our Republic. 
  "The attempt of the United States and some Western countries 
to put pressure on us through the UN Security Council hampers a 
complete solution of the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula 
and compels us to withdraw from the Nuclear Nonproliferation 
Treaty (NPT). 
  "We will have no other choice but to carry into practice the 
measures laid down in the March 12, 1993, statement of the 
government of our Republic in order to defend the national 
sovereignty and security of the country. 
  "A grave situation which may lead to confrontation and war 
has been created on the Korean peninsula again, and it is our 
stand to answer dialogue with dialogue, war with war under such 
situation." 
  Speaking at the conference that day, a member of the DPRK 
Parliamentary Union delegation said the nuclear issue on the 
Korean peninsula must be solved through DPRK-USA talks because 
it is the United States that introduced nuclear weapons into 
South Korea and has threatened the DPRK and invented a fiction 
of "suspected nuclear development" of the North. 
  "Pressure, threat and sanctions can neither be a solution to 
the problem, nor will they work with our people," he stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

