<H3> <TI>   Media Report on Anti-U.S. Rally by ROK Students </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Media Report on Anti-U.S. Rally by ROK Students </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Perry Portrait Burned </H4>

<F P=102> SK0204103594 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 0957 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0204103594 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 0957 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] This is news that just came in. This is news that 
just came in. 
  Approximately 500 college students in Seoul waged a 
demonstration struggle protesting the plan for deployment of 
Patriot missiles by burning a portrait of Perry. 
  According to a foreign news report, about 500 college 
students today burned the portrait of U.S. Defense Secretary 
Perry in protest of the U.S. plan to deploy Patriot missiles to 
South Korea and by shouting a slogan, "Yankee go home!" 
  The students denounced that Perry aggravated tension on the 
Korean peninsula by ordering the deployment of U.S. Patriot 
missiles to South Korea. They stated that North Korea denounced 
the deployment of Patriot missiles as an act of war against 
Pyongyang. 
  The students burned a portrait of Perry and models of 
Patriot missiles in a park in downtown Seoul. As a result, black 
smoke rose to the sky and the U.S. flag was tumbled all about on 
the ground. 
  About 200 police assumed a guard posture to block the park 
in an attempt to check the students' street demonstrations. 
  Some protesters, wearing masks, shouted the slogan, "We 
oppose the deployment of Patriot missiles!" 
  Approximately 400 riot police with shields and clubs were 
standing in front of the U.S. Embassy in the center of Seoul to 
repress possible disturbances. 
  In the past students have burned the U.S. flag and staged 
demonstrations in front of the U.S. Embassy opposing U.S. 
policies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

