Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discord With U.S. Over Issue Studied </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discord With U.S. Over Issue Studied </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0204130994 Seoul CHUNGANG ILBO in Korean 1 Apr 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> SK0204130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul CHUNGANG ILBO </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Chin Chang-nip from Washington] </F>
  [Text] The United States originally set the overall 
inspection [chonmyon sachal] of North Korean nuclear facilities 
by the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] and the 
exchange of North-South special envoys as a precondition for 
holding its third round of high-level talks with North Korea. 
It has been learned that the United States has expressed its 
intention to change its previous policy by attaching less 
importance to the exchange of North-South special envoys. The 
ROK, however, is opposed to this policy. The difference in 
opinions between the two countries regarding the issue has been 
disclosed. 
  The United States seems to believe it can make North Korea 
come to the negotiating table to discuss the nuclear issue if 
it attaches less importance to the exchange of special envoys. 
Also, it seems to believe that this can be another way to 
settle the North Korean nuclear issue, and that it will make 
some progress in resolving the nuclear issue when it holds the 
third round of high-level talks with North Korea, while the 
North and South are carrying out their exchange of special 
envoys. 
  The ROK worries that its efforts to denuclerize the Korean 
peninsula may be fruitless under the pretext of the improvement 
of North Korean-U.S. diplomatic relations when the United States 
excludes the exchange of North-South special envoys from its 
preconditions for holding the third U.S.-North Korean high-level 
talks or intends to discuss the issue at the third U.S.-North 
Korean talks as demanded by North Korea. 
  North Korea has maintained that it did not agree with the 
exchange of North-South special envoys in either the second 
round of North Korean-U.S. high-level talks or in the past 
unofficial contacts between the United States and North Korea in 
New York. It has said, however, that the exchange of 
North-South special envoys can be discussed as an agenda item at 
the third North Korean-U.S. high-level talks. The ROK and the 
United States have stressed: The North Korean side first 
proposed the exchange of North-South special envoys, then the 
South Korean side accepted it. Therefore, this is a 
precondition that should be kept by North Korea. 
  The ROK believes that although the North Korean nuclear 
issue 
involves the international community, it is, ultimately, a 
matter of the Korean peninsula. Accordingly, it worries that 
the issue of signing an agreement on the denuclerization on the 
Korean peninsula through the exchange of North-South special 
envoys would be discussed as an supplementary agenda item, when 
the issue of improving diplomatic relations between North Korea 
and the United States is being mainly discussed at the third 
U.S.-North Korean high-level talks. This is the reason for the 
ROK's objection. 
  The ROK believes that it is highly possible that North Korea 
would put forward the exchange of North-South special envoys as 
a condition for negotiations in improving relations with the 
United States if those negotiations are not going smoothly 
during the third U.S.-North Korean high-level talks. It also 
believes that if something goes wrong, the ROK will be the 
victim of negotiations between North Korea and the United States. 
  The United States is likely to review the change of the 
timing of the exchange of North-South special envoys, 
considering that it would be better to discuss other important 
issues after inducing North Korea to the negotiating table. 
  It has been learned, however, that the U.S. Government has 
not yet decided on its policy regarding the precondition for the 
third U.S.-North Korean high-level talks after the coordination 
of the timing of the exchange of the special envoys. 
  U.S. Secretary of Defense William Perry believes that North 
Korea's demands are an attempt to strengthen its position in 
negotiations with the United States by splitting the ROK and the 
United States and to exclude the ROK from participating in the 
negotiations by downgrading it as a third-party, not as a party 
concerned. Therefore, he said that it is the position of the 
Department of Defense to block in advance North Korea's attempts 
in order to resolve the North Korean nuclear issue. 
  He also said that the U.S. Forces stationed in South Korea, 
as well as the ROK Forces, must strengthen their combatant 
capability to prepare for the emergency situation on the 
assumption that the UN Security Council may impose sanctions on 
North Korea. He stressed that the United States and the ROK 
must closely cooperate with each other to strengthen their 
capability. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

