<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Han Denies Vice Minister Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Han Denies Vice Minister Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0404085994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0837 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0404085994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 4 (YONHAP) -- South Korean Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu said Monday that his government has never 
considered de-linking inter-Korean dialogue from Pyongyang's 
refusal to open fully its nuclear sites to international 
inspection. Asked about his position on remarks made Sunday by 
a senior South Korean Foreign Ministry official that Seoul was 
considering separating the nuclear problem from an envoy 
exchange, Minister Han said, "it seems to be his personal 
opinion." 
  While meeting reporters at the South Korean Embassy here, 
Han 
stressed that "Pyongyang must expose its nuclear sites to 
additional inspections by the International Atomic energy agency 
(IAEA) and allow an exchange of special envoys between South and 
North Korea if it wants to hold talks with the United States." 
  He said that "it is up to the IAEA" to make a decision on 
further checks of North Korea's suspect nuclear sites. However, 
"it will be between one month and six weeks after the United 
Nations Security Council adopted the chairman's declaration on 
March 31." 
  Han will meet with Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev 
in 
Moscow on April 14 to discuss the nuclear problem. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

