<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Returns From U.S., Japan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Returns From U.S., Japan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0404133294 Seoul YONHAP in English 1147 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0404133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 4 (YONHAP) -- Foreign Minister Han 
Sung-chu said here on Monday afternoon that he expects China 
will influence North Korea to fulfill its obligations spelled 
out in the UN Security Council president's recent statement over 
the nuclear question. The minister noted that the council 
president's statement was unanimously adopted and China played a 
positive role in the process. 
  While meeting with the press on arrival at Kimpo Airport 
from 
his tour of the United States and Japan, Han said South Korea, 
United States and Japan are carrying on efforts to persuade 
North Korea through China. 
  "If North Korea fails to fulfill the obligations within a 
specific period of time, the UN Security Council will take up 
the issue again, at which stage it would apparently take strong 
steps," he said. 
  The foreign minister also said that North Korea's acceptance 
of additional inspection by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA) is one of prerequisites, not the sole condition, 
for third-round U.S.-North Korea high-level talks. He thus held 
fast to the position that the U.S.-North Korea agreement made on 
last Feb. 25 remains valid. 
  Regarding the issue of the Team Spirit exercise, Minister 
Han 
declined to say whether the joint exercise would be resumed by 
saying South Korea is discussing the question with United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

