<H3> <TI>   Han Discusses Team Spirit With Secretary Perry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Han Discusses Team Spirit With Secretary Perry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0204015194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0138 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0204015194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 1 (YONHAP) -- South Korean Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu will leave here Saturday morning for 
Tokyo, where he will consult with Japanese Government leaders on 
the North Korean nuclear issue. Han is scheduled to meet with 
his Japanese counterpart Tsutomu Hata Sunday afternoon to 
explain the results of President Kim Yong-sam's visit to China 
and discuss the U.N. Security Council president's statement on 
North Korea adopted Friday. Han and Hata are expected to 
discuss follow-up measures on the nuclear dispute. 
  The South Korean foreign minister will call on Prime 
Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa on Monday to express Seoul's appreciation for 
Japanese cooperation in the Security Council's adoption of the 
presidential statement. They will discuss ways to maintain 
closer consultations on the North Korean question. 
  Prior to his departure, Han held intensive discussions with 
U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry on resumption of the 
military exercise Team Spirit and beefing up joint defense 
capabilities in South Korea. Han and Perry agreed that the two 
countries will decide on Team Spirit's timing in subsequent 
discussions considering developments in the nuclear impasse, and 
when Perry visits South Korea in mid-April, according to Foreign 
Ministry spokesman Chang Ki-ho. 
  In the hour-long meeting, Han and Perry shared the opinion 
that Friday's unanimous adoption of the Security Council 
statement would exert enormous pressure on North Korea. 
  Earlier, Han attended a policy debate attended by Peter 
Tarnoff, undersecretary of state for political affairs, Winston 
Lord, assistant secretary of state for East Asian and Pacific 
affairs, and Robert Gallucci, assistant secretary of state for 
political and military affairs. 

</TEXT>

