<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wider Market Opening for U.S. Cars Planned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wider Market Opening for U.S. Cars Planned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0204002394 Seoul YONHAP in English 2328 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0204002394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 2 (YONHAP) -- Seoul is planning wider 
market opening to American automobiles and planning to start 
negotiations with the United States, trade officials said 
Saturday. The measure comes as Washington showed readiness to 
launch a full-scale drive into the South Korean market with a 
warning of invoking 301 trade provision against Seoul. The U.S. 
National Trade Estimate (NTE) made available Friday criticized 
Seoul's formal and informal barriers that have "virtually closed 
Korea's 1.1 million-unit passenger car market to U.S.-built 
motor vehicle exports." 
  Initial plans include gradually lowering the import tariff 
from the current 10 percent to around 7.5 percent, the officials 
said. An inter-ministerial meeting led by vice trade, industry 
and resources minister is planned on Monday to set the details. 
  The government will start first with improving non-tariff 
barriers, such as active public message that the government will 
not impose disadvantages to those buying foreign cars, allowing 
more and larger show rooms and giving air time for 
advertisements during prime time slots. These issues are likely 
to be tabled formally at a meeting between South Korean Trade 
Minister Kim Chol-su and U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor 
this month during the signing period of the Uruguay Round [UR] 
agreement in Morocco, the officials said on condition of 
anonymity. 
  The Trade, Industry and Resources Ministry has been the main 
opposer but very recently agreed to consider the auto market 
opening more positively, according to the officials. 
  Seoul and Washington had agreed to address the issue at the 
minister level during last December's bilateral UR negotiations. 
This agreement is included in their record of understanding. 
U.S. requests include import tariff reduction schedule, revision 
to the current local tax system where taxes are levied according 
to engine size, consequently working against larger American 
models. Washington officials suggest levying taxes according to 
the level of fuel efficiency instead of engine size. 
  The NTE points out that imported cars in South Korea 
accounted for only 0.2 percent of Korea's market in 1933. The 
blatant anti-import campaign of the mid-1980s has waned but 
similar signals still continue, the report said. 
  "Korea's duty of 10 percent compares highly unfavorably to 
the 2.5 percent duty assessed Korean automobiles entering the 
United States," it said. "The U.S. objective is to ensure that 
U.S. motor vehicles have the same access to the Korean market as 
Korean motor vehicles have to the U.S. market," it said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4650 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas064_d_94020" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-064 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul `Apparently Split' Over U.S. Auto Market </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seoul `Apparently Split' Over U.S. Auto Market </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0404033094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0256 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0404033094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 4 (YONHAP) -- The government is 
apparently split over how to respond to mounting U.S. pressure 
for wider access to Korea's motor vehicle market due to 
different interpretations of the wording in a "record of 
understanding" exchanged between Seoul and Washington during the 
Uruguay Round [UR] negotiations last year. 
  The Foreign Ministry advocates early tariff concessions on 
automobile imports, abolition of limits on showrooms for foreign 
cars and approval of advertising as demanded by the United 
States, while the Trade, Industry and Energy Ministry firmly 
opposes lower tariffs and early liberalization of the 
distribution market before the scheduled January 1996. 
  The Foreign Ministry says concessions are inevitable, 
pointing to the phrase "reduction in the tariffs on motor 
vehicles will be addressed at the ministerial level," 
interpreting "address" as meaning "announce" and therefore a 
promise on future cuts. 
  As Washington, citing the record, is strongly demanding 
tariff reductions and predicting Korea will inevitably have to 
bow to its request, the Foreign Ministry wants to resolve the 
issue quickly. 
  U.S. Deputy Assistant Trade Representative Peter Collins 
referred to the record of understanding to demand immediate 
tariff cuts on car imports in trade talks in Seoul early last 
month. 
  The Trade, Industry and Energy Ministry, however, sees 
things 
differently. It interprets "address" to mean "discuss" as it is 
often regarded in business, saying it thus cannot be a promise 
on tariff cuts as insisted by the United States. 
  Even if it is a promise, the reduction refers to tariff 
offers because the record was made in the UR negotiations, the 
trade ministry argues. 
  Offering and actual tariff rates may be the same to the 
United States, but they are two different things to Korea, the 
ministry says, adding that Seoul only needs to change the 
offering rates. 
  In its country schedule, Korea had offered to maintain an 
80-percent tariff on motor vehicle imports until 2004. 
  The Trade Ministry immediately issued a press release that 
the government has no plans to lower tariffs on car imports nor 
to open the distribution market earlier than scheduled, 
contrasting with earlier reports quoting Foreign Ministry 
officials as saying that Seoul has decided to accept the U.S. 
demand on tariff cuts on car imports. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4651 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas064_d_94021" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-064 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Strengthening of `Policy Coordination' Studied </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Strengthening of `Policy Coordination' Studied </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0404084394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0816 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0404084394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 4 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam's 
office may strengthen the government's overall policy 
coordination as senior administration officials continue to 
contradict one another on the North Korean nuclear dispute and 
other foreign and national security issues. As part of the plan 
reported Monday, the presidential office would either form a 
consultative body comprising Chongwadae, the National 
Unification Board, the foreign and defense ministries and the 
Agency for National Security Planning, or beef up Chongwadae's 
team on foreign and national security affairs. 
  One Chongwadae official acknowledged Monday that confusion 
has emerged in the government's foreign and security policy 
"because of Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu's attitude, Ambassador 
to China Hwang Pyong-tae's recent remarks and Vice Foreign 
Minister Hong Sun-yong's publicly expressed opinion" over the 
weekend. 
  "Chongwadae is undertaking a study from various angles in 
order to strengthen the coordinating function of its foreign and 
security policy," the official said, requesting anonymity. 
  The consultative body is being considered because of the 
limitations of the current system including conferences of 
security-related ministers, chaired by the president, and the 
prime minister's strategic sessions with high government 
officials. But the new body would not be like the United 
States' National Security Council (NSC) since the present 
security-related ministers' meetings perform a similar function, 
he said. 
  Alternatively, Chongwadae may beef up the office of the 
senior presidential secretary for foreign and national security 
affairs since it is the president who makes the final decision 
on all foreign and security policy, he said. 
  Another Chongwadae official said, "following Ambassador 
Hwang's inappropriate remarks, our foreign policy was once again 
plunged into confusion when Vice Foreign Minister Hong suggested 
on Sunday that the government should consider dropping its 
demand for a special envoy exchange with North Korea as a 
precondition for a third round of U.S.-North Korean high-level 
talks." 
  "It has become an urgent government task to strengthen 
policy 
coordination if we are to establish an effective North Korea 
strategy," the official said. 
  "The weakest point in our foreign policy in the past started 
with showing all our cards," the official pointed out. 
Henceforth, the government will keep secret its negotiating 
strategy while beefing up the publicity function, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4652 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas064_d_94022" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-064 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry To Extend Defense Posture Reinforcement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry To Extend Defense Posture Reinforcement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0204025694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0251 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0204025694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 2 (YONHAP) -- The Defense Ministry said 
Saturday that it has decided to extend a measure to strengthen 
the country's defense posture in preparation for an emergency, 
which began last November and originally was to end at the end 
of March. The ministry said the measure must be extended because 
North Korea has kept heightening tension on the peninsula by 
reinforcing its military training. 
  The ministry decided to watch North Korea's military moves 
by 
operating a 24-hour security monitoring system on the Korean 
peninsula. 
  Meanwhile, the ministry lifted the special state of alert, 
ordered for President's Kim Yong-sam's visits to Japan and 
China, as of 5:30 P.M. last Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

