<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Regret Expressed Over DPRK Statement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Regret Expressed Over DPRK Statement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0404054394 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 0303 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0404054394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report from the "NHK News" program] </F>
  [Text] North Korea [DPRK] has issued a statement on its 
decision to refuse the UN Security Council [UNSC] request that 
it accept inspection of its nuclear facilities by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). Commenting on the 
statement, the Japanese Government said it was very regrettable 
that the country failed to fully understand the international 
community's real intention. 
  The government expressed particularly grave concern that the 
North Korean statement, in which the country said it had been 
forced to resume its suspended nuclear development, may become a 
decisive factor in leaving the country isolated in the 
international community. 
  On the other hand, the government intends to make additional 
efforts to influence North Korea to accept inspections of its 
nuclear facilities, this time in cooperation with China, which 
still has influence in North Korea. 
  Meanwhile, Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa held talks today 
with South Korean Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu, who is 
currently visiting Japan. In the talks they shared the view 
that China's cooperation is necessary to solving the issue of 
nuclear inspections of North Korea. 
  Foreign Minister Han said the significance of the UNSC's 
presidential statement adopted at the end of March was that it 
held China to a sense of obligation to make progress on the 
issue. He said there was an impression that China was trying to 
play a more positive role than before. 
  In response, Prime Minister Hosokawa said it is necessary 
for 
the countries concerned -- namely Japan, the United States, and 
South Korea as well as China -- to cooperate in influencing 
North Korea to solve the issue. They confirmed the intention to 
continue to urge North Korea to accept the inspections by the 
end of this month [April]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

