<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. F-15 Fighter Crashes in Okinawa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. F-15 Fighter Crashes in Okinawa </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    City Assembly To Protest </H4>

<F P=102> OW0504021894 Naha OKINAWA TIMES in Japanese 5 Apr 94 Morning 
Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0504021894 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha OKINAWA TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Okinawa Municipal Assembly (with Heiwa Yaga as 
speaker) called an extraordinary session at 1800 [0900 GMT] on 
the afternoon of 4 April at which members unanimously adopted a 
resolution and a statement of opinions strongly protesting to 
U.S. military authorities about the U.S. Air Force F-15 fighter 
crash in the morning. 
  An assembly delegation is scheduled to present these 
documents to the U.S. Forces Okinawa Area Coordinator, the Naha 
Defense Facilities Administration Bureau, the prefectural 
governor, and the prefectural assembly speaker on the morning of 
5 April. 
  The resolution and statement of opinions point out: "The 
Kadena ammunition dump is located near the accident site, and in 
neighboring areas there are also stock farms, recreation 
centers, and villages. As a single mistake could have resulted 
in a disaster involving citizens, it was a serious shock to our 
people and they are now uneasy." 
  As well as criticizing the U.S. military for its deficient 
maintenance and management of military aircraft, the documents 
reiterate the people's great anger. 
  "Okinawa city residents have been compelled to coexist with 
the largest U.S. military base in the Far East. And as far as 
they are concerned, they feel this accident vividly demonstrates 
their fears that inevitably result from the existence of 
military bases." 
  Touching on previous accidents, as well as the fact that 
military aircraft regularly fly over residential areas, the 
documents state "our people are continually exposed to the 
danger of being deprived of their lives and property." 
  Therefore, while strongly demanding that measures be taken 
to 
prevent any further accidents, the assembly wants the cause of 
the accident be publicized for prefectural residents as soon as 
possible, maintenance work on all aircraft strengthened, and a 
ban on aircraft flying until proper maintenance work is ensured. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

