<H3> <TI>   U.S. F-15 Fighter Crashes in Okinawa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. F-15 Fighter Crashes in Okinawa </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    MOFA Official Meets With Ota </H4>

<F P=102> OW0504080594 Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO in Japanese 5 Apr 94 Morning 
Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0504080594 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Toshiyuki Takano, councilor with the North American 
Affairs Bureau of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs [MOFA], called 
on Okinawa Prefectural Governor Ota on 4 April. During the 
meeting, Mr. Takano promised that the Foreign Ministry will do 
its best to resolve problems arising from the U.S. military 
bases on Okinawa. 
  The Foreign Ministry official is in Okinawa to tour U.S. 
military bases, and an F-15 Eagle fighter crashed during his 
stay in the island. It is said that during his meeting with 
Donald R. Gardner, commander of U.S. Forces Okinawa, at Camp 
Courtney, he asked the commander to conduct a "thorough 
investigation into the cause of the crash and take thorough 
measures to prevent a recurrence of such a crash." In response, 
the commander said, "I understand." 
  During the meeting with Mr. Takano, Okinawa Prefectural 
Governor Ota said: "The Okinawans are increasingly reacting 
against intensifying live-fire exercises and flight training by 
U.S. Forces on Okinawa. The presence of Naha Military Port 
stands in the way of developing the free trade zone. Under this 
situation, the crash occurred and I have difficulty dealing with 
problems, including the crash accident, arising from the U.S. 
military bases in Okinawa." 
  In response, Mr. Takano said, "The Foreign Ministry will do 
its best to smoothly resolve problems arising from the U.S. 
military bases on Okinawa." 

</TEXT>

