<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Komeito Head Backs Coalition Consultative Body </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Komeito Head Backs Coalition Consultative Body </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0404164294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 2 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0404164294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 1 April, Komeito Secretary General Yuichi 
Ichikawa said he felt that now that the political reform bills 
have been enacted, the ruling coalition parties should reexamine 
agreements they made last July and work out agreements regarding 
such issues as security policies and tax system reform, in 
particular. He made the remark during a news conference at a 
hotel in Kyoto, where he made an appearance during part of his 
stumping tour. Specifically, Ichikawa proposed a plan to set up 
a new "council on basic issues" (tentative name) under the 
coalition party representatives' conference to coordinate 
policies among the ruling coalition parties in preparation for 
the next general election. He plans to formally present the 
proposal at a 4 April representatives meeting. 
  Regarding the political situation since the enactment of the 
political reform bills, Ichikawa said: "The situations at home 
and abroad have drastically changed since the coalition 
government's inauguration last July, as exemplified by such 
developments as the DPRK's suspected nuclear arms development." 
He then stressed the need for working out agreements among 
ruling coalition parties to promote cooperation in the next 
general election, saying: "We should work out both an agreement 
on mutually essential points and a new outline of policies." 
  In the ruling coalition alliance, a plan to set up a "policy 
study group" was recently shelved due to opposition by such 
parties as the Social Democratic Party of Japan. This study 
group was expected to serve as a stepping stone toward the 
formation of a new party to unify the coalition partners into a 
single party. In this regard, Ichikawa said: "In the future, 
even should the ruling coalition parties decide not to move 
toward (the formation of) a new party, they cannot cooperate in 
elections unless their basic policies are coordinated." 
  Regarding the process of making adjustments among ruling 
coalition parties in selecting candidates for the next general 
election, Ichikawa said: "I expected the process to begin in 
April, but the issue of setting up a policy study group has 
created unnecessary misunderstandings, resulting in straining 
the relations (among the coalition partners). Therefore, there 
may be a slight delay." He thus indicated the process is 
expected to start later than originally planned. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4685 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas065__a94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
