<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. F-15 Fighter Crashes in Okinawa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. F-15 Fighter Crashes in Okinawa </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Governor Ota Reacts </H4>

<F P=102> OW0504062994 Naha OKINAWA TIMES in Japanese 5 Apr 94 Morning 
Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0504062994 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha OKINAWA TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Governor Masahide Ota's regular unofficial meeting 
with reporters at 1100 [0200 GMT] on 4 April suddenly became an 
emergency news conference on the crash of the U.S. Forces' F-15 
fighter. The incident has seriously shocked the prefectural 
government, and Ota has issued direct instructions to his Base 
Affairs Office to confirm the details of the accident. 
  Prefectural Policy Coordinator Choko Takayama, and Tatsuo 
Matayoshi, director of the Governor's Office, are now busy 
arranging the lodging of a protest with the U.S. Forces Okinawa 
area coordinator, and Kadena Air Base commander. They are also 
demanding an investigation into the cause of the crash. 
  The accident happened during Ota's preparations for the 
visit 
to Okinawa of U.S. Ambassador to Japan Walter Mondale on 10 
April. He is now working on how to petition Mondale for 
solutions to the prefecture's base issues. 
  Ota said at the news conference: "It is extremely 
unfortunate and regrettable. Time and again, we have asked U.S. 
Forces and the U.S. Consulate General to take measures to 
prevent accidents. Each time, we are told that they are looking 
into the causes. Does this mean that as long as there are 
military bases in Okinawa, there will be no way to prevent 
accidents? We will exert even greater efforts in asking for the 
return of the bases." He reemphasized his position that the 
return of the military bases forms a major pillar of the 
prefecture's administrative policy. 
  The latest accident demonstrated once again that Kadena Air 
Base is inherently dangerous. Ota is scheduled to visit the 
United States in late May to discuss base issues. During this 
visit he will probably demand in strong terms that the U.S. 
Government take firm measures to "prevent any more accidents." 
  At present, takeoff and landing exercises at Kadena are 
conducted over civilian residential areas every day. The crash 
site of the F-15 fighter on 4 April was within the vicinity of 
the Kadena Arms Depot. One slip could have led to a major 
explosion, and brought about a disaster. 
  The F-15 fighter crash occurred with Kadena Air Base still 
unable to publish the findings of its investigation into the 
helicopter crash in September 1993. For this, the prefectural 
government is greatly dissatisfied with U.S. Forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4715 </DOCNO>
